text: FOR THOSE WHO ARE CONFUSED...  Its a Reboot of the classic Universal Mummy starring Boris Karloff (Not the Brendan Fraser movies). But its gonna be part of the Universal Monsters Cinematic Universe. This film is also in canon with Dracula Untold.   Back in the 1940s Universal were the first to create the cinematic universe genre with there monster movies. They had Dracula, Frankenstein, The Wolf Man, The Mummy and so forth in separate movies and sequels, then brought them together for films like Frankenstein Meets The Wolfman and House Of Dracula.   So this is Universal (In an odd way) going back to their roots with the Monster Mash of the 40s, but its also because everyone is cashing in on what Marvel did with the Crossover Genre.

text: Everyone, allow me to nerd out...this movie IS NOT a remake of the 1999 version, nor is it a remake of the 1932 version. It is instead an R rated reboot by request of Universal Studios and is contracted to be the first in a series of horror reboots featuring Frankenstein, Dracula, The Wolf Man, and Creature From the Black Lagoon. So this has nothing to do with any other movies other than the fact that its source of licensing was Universal's original Mummy played by Boris Karloff.

text: I'm fed up with all the ignorant Brendan Fraser fanboys/fangirls in every goddamn comment section of this movie. This is the year 2016, the age of Internet. Use google and READ ARTICLES WHICH LITERALLY ARE HUNDREDS about this. This is NOT a reboot of Fraser's mummy, and it is the start of a new CINEMATIC MONSTER UNIVERSE WITH DRACULA (REMEMBER DRACULA UNTOLD?), FRANKENSTEIN, THE INVISIBLE MAN (JOHNNY DEPP), DR. JEKYL (RUSSEL CROWE WHO IS IN THE GODDAMN TRAILER) and so on. This is neither a reboot of Fraser's movie, nor set within the same universe. And for one, BRENDAN FRASER'S movie was not the original Mummy movie at all, it was a remake itself. The original mummy movie was from 1932, ffs. Just take off the rose-tinted glasses while  of you are nostalgic about that Fraser trilogy. Or need I remind you all that the second and especially the third movie SUCKED ASS? People have short-term memory, I guess. Still, there is no excuse to be as ignorant as all of you folks are about this in the year 2016. Google, Yahoo, Bing - USE IT. They literally spam articles about this movie and the planned monster universe. All of you are also the same folks who go into that new Kong trailer and scream "Why reboot the Peter Jackson version boohoo" without realizing that that flick isn't a reboot either of that particular version. People are ignorant as shit and just act like fanboys/fangirls.

author: Halie Hope

text: Man, I'm a huge fan of the original Mummy franchise. I thought the 3rd one was already an abomination and an unnecessary film to make. Now they make another one?  And really, it feels more like The Mummy: Apocalypse without the mutants than anything else.  This is a huge problem with Hollywood right now, in my opinion. They have an template of what they think works. And while that template does work sometimes, they take that and try to force every other film into that box. The majority of action-adventure movies are feeling like carbon-copies of each other with swapped details rather than unique stories.   And stop it with the overuse of bad cgi!! It really takes away from the immersion! A little bit of bad cgi is fine, but when a movie relies on it to do the big sfx, then it's a problem, and the movie feels more like cartoon than a live-action flick. Not every movie has to try to copy Marvel.   Goddammit, they just couldn't leave this franchise alone. They can't leave any franchise alone. Any franchise which even has the smallest bit of success and notoriety will be ruined. And The Mummy wasn't even that successful or good. It's almost cult following status, I feel.   And why Tom Cruise? This isn't a spy movie. Hell, I'd rather Chris Pratt play the lead role instead.

text: You know why audiences are so bored of movies lately? Shit like this. Another totally generic and formulaic action movie with a very eye-catching cgi villain that,  while seemingly not very much like the mummy with Brendon Frasier, feels alot like Hollywood guys trying to cash in on the same ideas-abd certainly blatantly reusing the name to fuck with future people looking for the other movie only to get this Tom Cruise suck fest. It's so tiring to watch generic film after unnecessary sequel after unnecessary overly cgi-ed reboot after bastardized childhood nostalgia movie adaptation. Just get with the original shit or find a way to divert money to the indie scene where at least some of it is still original. Some, I say with utmost care,  because even indie films have gotten a bit contrived and bullshitty. I'm not saying every film has to be a winner, but like... Why are so many Hollywood films these days not even as good as 70s/80s/90s B movies? And I LOVE shitty films,  don't get me wrong-- Jupiter Ascending is a perfect example of amazing modern shit storm that I crave,  but seriously this looks like it's in the bad zone between ok and total garbage where it doesn't swing back round again,  you know? Also Tom Cruise... So overrated.

text: I actually wrote a story similar to this. In it, this wealthy, fat museum guy who can summon demons using mystical items/artifacts, funds an expedition to the tomb of the Lost Queen of Egypt. He does this because the ancient Queen was a skilled enchantress who had obtained true immortality and whose destructive power exceeded that of an army. For some mysterious reason, four of the most powerful sorcerers in Egypt had sealed her within the coffin. Basically, he wants to learn the secret to immortality.   So, some of the people he sends are people who actually want to learn and a few are sent who know what the real purpose of this mission is. When the group  brings the coffin across the chasm to where they are standing, deep underground, an earthquake sound appears and the black five-headed dragon Gora appears and starts butchering up and frying everyone with flames. Very few people are able to get to the surface and much fewer can get on an airplane out of there. The, I think, five individuals who know the secret mission keep the coffin on their plane and try to head to the museum. But, the enormous dragon relentlessly pursues them in the sky.  Then, one of the people on the plane use a mystical item, the Eye of Ra, a golden triangular artifact with an eye at its center, to send the dragon to another dimension. However, this requires one sacrifice so one of the guys on the plane gets sucked up into the Eye of Ra. So now, there are four guys on the plane and three of them complain that they shouldn't have done that. But, the guy who used the item argues that they couldn't get rid of the dragon any other way and that besides, the boss promised them a huge reward, and if there are fewer people to share it among, then everyone gets more.   So, these four guys reach the museum at night where the crazy fat guy is waiting. While the people were on an expedition, he had made preparations summoning one hundred druid demons with one really big death-reaper like demon called Death Keeper (I think?). He has the coffin brought in and he examines the hieroglyphs which indicate that it takes four human sacrifices to unlock the Queen. When the four guys ask for the money, he gives a crazy laugh and betrays them by using the Eye of Ra to sacrifice all four of them. So, the Immortal Queen appears.  She awakens and the fat guy tells her where she is and what he wants. She tells him that she doesn't really know about the whole immortality thing. So, he has the Death Keeper strike a chain into her soul to pull it out and she falls forward. But, when he tells her that this is the power of one hundred human souls, she's not impressed. Then, she generates the power of more than one hundred souls, pulls out a sword by magic and shatters the chain causing all the demons to disappear into smoke and her sword disappears too. Despite being a modern sorcerer, he greatly underestimated the Immortal Queen's magic and she gives him amnesia. Then, she leaves, curious to learn about this new world she had arrived in.   And that's as far as I got in writing the story.

text: I was hoping to see an intelligent rendition of the Mummy for the first time since the 30s! There are no writers or directors anymore who understand true terror is not about blowing everything up and having Spanky Hands Cruise live through it all!! If I was the Mummy I would be scared shitless of Cruise, because this mofo badass can't be blown up, even in the sky when his airplane predictably goes up!   Another highly boring, predictable piece of thoughtless crap! Movie producers, writers and directors should have to be forced into watching the truly great films from the 1930s through the early 1960s. Those folks knew how to create real suspense, and fear in the audiences.   The last Wolfman came very close to it. That was a film in danger of being great!  Lon Chaney, now there's the real Wolfman!!   Nosferatu, watch that movie!! Even the old silent version was true horror!! No explosions, no predictable annihilation of entire city blocks, because Mrs Mummy is having a bad hair and wrappings day.   "Horror"movies? Where? Pieces of shit movies? Everywhere...sigh  Please, someone write a real classic Mummy movie. Not the Brendan Frasier Disney version, and not this latest piece of crap!! Watch the old original horror flicks and learn.  Watch Hush Hush Sweet Charlotte, and I guarantee that you'll be sleeping with the damned lights on for a month!!

text: This reboot just confuses tf out of me. They pick Tom Cruise for it, and he's *older* than Brendan Fraser. The guy is 54(but doesn't look as such. What is with some of these actors looking like they never age?). Usually with these reboots/remakes, actors that are younger than the previous ones, are picked. Not older ones. And what's funny, is that when I look at this movie, I see The Mummy. It looks more like a sequel that you'd expect(mainly when it comes to visuals) if it was made nowadays, a sequel that could've happened, but was stuck in developmental hell, and had changes, one of which, Brendan Fraser being replaced by Tom Cruise. This reboot is just right on that line, between a reboot/remake being good, or complete, unrecognizable garbage. At best, I see this film being average or slightly below average.  There's one positive thing though. For once, in a modern film with Egyptian stuff in it, the Egyptian part *isn't* white-washed. I checked, the actress, Sofia Boutella, isn't white. She's Algerian-French. Algeria is in North Africa. They actually got someone from Africa in someway, for an Egyptian role. Props to Universal. Don't know why they this Mummy looking more like The Enchantress though.  But Universal are the same ones behind The Great Wall, and the main protagonist in that film, is played by a White actor, instead of an Asian actor, so WTF is going there? Then again, that film is coming out in China this month, so maybe Universal learned what all of these studios should've gotten through their heads by now.

text: I hate to have to say this, but I'm kind of  disappointed that these classic horror movies are being remade into action/adventure films. What's wrong with actually keeping them horror? Why do we need bloated special effects and massive action set pieces? If I were running this monsters shared universe, I'd either make it campy but faithful like Monster Squad, or make it gothic and dripping with atmosphere like Penny Dreadful. Hell, just buy the rights for the show to continue it on the big screen. It's already a got all of the classic horror movie monsters, and they even hinted at the mummy this last season. Anyway, thanks for reading this mini-rant!

text: Ok, the original Mummy was a horror movie. The 1999 remake made things more action-y, but still retained a sort of horror-esque spirit to it. The sequels went off the deep-end (even though I enjoyed The Mummy Returns for what it was) and made things too much action/adventure to really still be called The Mummy. Now this... is just straight up action-schlock, it seems. Why even call it The Mummy? Does that name even really hold all that much mass appeal? Was anybody itching to see another movie that was just called "The Mummy"? You can make an action/adventure movie about A mummy coming back from the dead, without having to call it "The Mummy"... I mean, if you're gonna cast Tom Cruise anyway just to give it some mass appeal, then why bother ape-ing "The Mummy" as well?  I wouldn't mind seeing an actual remake of The Mummy. One that is actually a straight-forward horror movie. But this... is one big pile of WTF.

text: I'm an old school Universal Horror fan. That being said, as much as I love those classic films, I also understand that it's foolish to expect these reboot movies to be anything like those vintage flicks. I'm very excited to see how the casting for this incarnation of "The Mummy" has been so thoughtfully done. Tom Cruise is an excellent actor, highly effective in all of his roles, and he should really bring amazing things to this project. Russell Crow is wonderful beyond words, and will surely lean a real gravitas to his part.   However, the casting of Sofia Boutella promises to be the biggest thrill to be found here, and her creature design (from what little I've been able to see thus far) appears quite extraordinary, and could easily fall into the realm of iconic in its own right. (BTW, I loved the featured close-up on Ms. Boutella's eyes, and the way it clearly signified upon the famous Boris Karloff / Mummy image. Nice touch.)

text: Y'know, what made the original Mummy so likeable was that the threat was pretty much on a smaller, more personal scale. The characters were in close quarters with the horrors of the tombs and Imhotep himself, and that made it more intense and more personal. This is large-scale like every other disaster movie lately (Uhm, X-Men Apocalypse?) and it diminishes what it has to bring to the table because we've seen it before, and believe me, we're bored of it.   Cool, the evil mummy is a woman, that's great, she could be badass, but destroying London again? Yeah, I think I'll pass.

text: Eh.... Again, hadn't it been for the tittle i would not have been able to guess this was a Mummy film. You know, sometimes sticking to the rout of one of the older movies isn't such a bad thing. Doing something different is all fine and cool... But this is so different i just don't know that i know what this is anymore. Now it's some kinda female demonic bitch with superpowers buried in something that doesn't really look egyptian... This does not look like anything Mummy esk at all. The thing i loved so much about the 1999 movie is that it fealt like a fucking dventure back in the old days. Shit looked egyptian. It looked kinda scary and exiting... When ever i watch those movies i just get goosebumps because it's so exiting and great. + The actual Mummy design is like scary as fuck when you think about it. And he has his Mummy soldiers that are actually rather creepy... And he slowly becomes more and more human.... Sorta expanding on the concept of the original where he just all of a sudden is human and no one expects him to be a actual Mummy. The 199 version is my favorite. Here... The Epyptian style is just raped to the point where it isn't egyptian. The Mummy doesn't look like a Mummy... They seem to just be playing on SEX as per usual. ''Oh look, a sexy woman with superpowers and she is bad''. I'm actually expeecting a scene where she tries to seduce someone with being all like ''Look at my titts, look at my ass... Grab me, fuck me and DIE''. That's not The Mummy... I actually hoped that they would manage to do something great. I was hoping for a return to form.... Back to the horror roots. But instead they made this generic pice of garbage.... Had it not had the MUMMY name on there it wouldn't botter me at all. But this uses the name of a OLD OLD series of movies that is well respected and loved by many and it totally butchers it... Sorry, this is a shit trailer. The movie looks shit and i won't be checking it out until i can get it on like a 3 Blu-rays for the price of one. No thank you Universal... Go back to the drwaing bord. Rename this shit and give me a real Mummy movie. And the fact that you plan to build a Universe around this makes me even more sad.... text: I'm not too big a fan of this at the moment. An article I read said this was a form of reboot of The Mummy movies I grew up watching. This isn't a reboot, it's an entirely different movie. Which is fine, to be perfectly honest. I forget which article it was I read (I didn't pay attention in that respect). But I think they're confused though.   As far as the trailer goes: A.) That scream "AHHH! AHHH!...........AHHHHH!" I love it so much; too hilarious! But... B.) They need to hire a better film editor because holy shit this trailer looked so bad compared to others I've seen "recently" (I.E.: Not very recent, actually).  - I liked the trailer for The Force Awakens a lot. Before the movie came out I was only recently introduced to the Star Wars movie series. Even with that very little attachment/exposure to the series the Episode 7 trailer got me crying. LOL... But that's just my opinion and should not be taken too seriously. Let's be honest here, I'm no movie critic. The movie could be a huge hit and the trailer isn't portraying it that masterfully. I just like what I like and dislike what I dislike. That's all there is to it. xD  What do you guys think of the trailer/movie? Was the trailer done well to you, or was there a past movie trailer you watched that you liked far better?

text: So, we know that this is a cinematic universe movie with the classic movie monsters.      Crowe is Jekyll and likely will not give us the satisfaction of a Hyde reveal in the first film (unless they are truly foolish and waste all their best material in the first film). He seems to be playing Samuel L Jackson's Director Fury in this.      The big reveal will be who/what Cruise is. The fact that he dies and comes back shows that he is someone/thing.      The Universal slate includes "the Wolf Man, the Invisible Man, Abraham van Helsing, the Creature from the Black Lagoon, and the Bride of Frankenstein." That rules them out. You wouldn't have a future leading as the reveal - so that rules out anything listed as Cruise.      Now, look at Cruise's hair, his unkillability/durability, and the way he hefts that log when he goes to face the mummy girl.       Cruise is the monster (Frankenstein's).

Can't it be something new and aside from the previous movie with the same title? Even the antagonist of this movie has nothing to do (well... except for her name... in a way) with the previous movie.  That's like if you were to make a movie about zombies, call it something like "Wasteland of the Dead" and people who start complaining that they prefer "Land of the Dead" and it would automatically be a rip-off of the previous movie.  I mean... it's not like the word Mummy had only to be used with the movies related to 99's The Mummy, right?

text: As someone who grew up with the original Mummy movies (in fact I grew up watching them instead of other iconic "childhood" series like Indiana Jones or Star Wars) I loved them for their cheesiness and strange,kind of awkward charm. To me they'll always be the perfect B+ movies. While I don't think this movie will be bad just because it's a remake, I do hope they keep some of the weirdness. Giant sand faces, beetles crawling under people's skin and eating their brains, giant, poorly CGI'd man-scorpions, that's the kind of stuff that gave those movies their identity. Hell even the Tomb of the Dragon emperor had it with Jet Li constantly puking up clay over himself and getting refrozen and shit. Also I'm not sure about the whole "epicness" this movie is setting up. Yeah the originals had pretty high stakes involved each time, but it was usually people fighting out in the desserts and dark tombs, not entire cities being wiped out. Makes it seem less like a daring adventure and more like a disaster movie.

text: Am I the only one that realized that billions of people thinks "The Mummy" is a reboot of the Brendan Fraser Mummy series when it's not. This Mummy film is a reinterpretation of the 1940's Horror Icon Mummy. Such Icons include Dracula, Swamp Thing, Dr. Jeckle and Mr. Hyde, Wolf Man. I know most of you are post Twilight generation but don't judge a flim on the base of different franchises with similar names. This is "THE" True Mummy that can put fear in the hearts of men and display Godlike Egyptian power. An Horror and action icon. This IS NOT based on action adventure with Brendan Fraser. Please spread this message. because I'm tired of pussified horror Icons and look forward to a shared Monster Universe where Van Helsing can show up in a Mummy based movie, or Dracula could fight The Mummy in an undead war. I'm tired of pussy Vampires, Wolves and the overdone Zombies!

One would certainly think a younger man would have been chosen.  He can't get enough KUDOS for being the action hero of a "fingers-crossed" blockbuster at age FIFTY THREE!!!! Yes, some older guys limp painfully through endless franchise sequels, but just from the trailer, you can see he is in peak form and HE LOOKS VIBRANT. I've heard not only is he more daring than many younger men but also he plays it safe and has a life-time knowledge of stunts which is something the young bucks don't have.  And he is once again in a movie with STRONG FEMALE LEADS because he actively promotes women in movies.  AND, he speaks up for mental patients who often exist in deplorable conditions in asylums.  I don't mind making a special effort to see Cruise opening weekend. I'm looking forward to the running and the motorcycle June 2017!

text: This looks ridiculous.  Way to ruin a cult classic, Universal.  Tom Cruise? I lost my lunch when I saw his hideous mug in the trailer. On top of that, this teaser has "serious" and "action flick" written all over it in blatantly cliched lettering.  The Mummy (1999) was more of a macabre comedy than anything else. It barely took itself seriously, and it was a smashingly good cinema. Practically timeless in its entertainment value.  But the casting and framing in this Trailer says it all: Mission Impossible VII: Project Divine Tom Cruise Imitates Jesus-Keanu Reeves Role and Saves the Planet from an Ancient Pseudo-Sexy Egyptian Evil in Order to Save a Romantic Interest.  In other words, it's total cut and paste. New logo on the same tired old product. Just another lazy as beans money grubbing institutionalized cinema production.  Think I'm pouring salt on this? Just wait. I can't wait to read the viewer's criticism.  Bang up job, you can-eaters.

text: Ok, trailer looks good but then again most trailers do. My question is and please forgive because I didn't read all the comments...what the heck is Dr. Jekyll doing here with the mummy and who is Cruise suppose to really be. I know some say it's a revival of the Mummy movie series, others say it a reboot of Universal Monster movies. To me it looks like a big screen version of Penny Dreadful (Showtime series, now off the air). Could Cruise's character be for instance (I say this because he looks immortal or at least is hard to hurt).....Dorian Grey perhaps or the monster maybe (I have seen many many Frankenstein versions and he not always...what is considered to be ugly..I have a page called Classic HorrorMovies on FB....dealing not only with classic horror but all movies from the silent era to the 1980s...sometimes I go to the 90s/2000s but that is a rarity. I don't claim to know everything about horror movies or movies in general but I love watching them and  researching them)...or even.....just go with it or try....Ramses (you know like the character sort of like from Anne Rices novel...The Mummy, a good guy) or lets go with Imhotep. Well that's my opinion anyway...oh as for the Rick O'Connell series...too bad Rachel Weisz thought she was too old to play a mother of a grown child, not that I am knocking Maria Bello. I also hoping they would do the one they sort of hinted at......finding mummies in Peru maybe.

text: Well at least this one has a line from an old Universal Studios horror film ("To a new world of Gods and Monsters!" from "Bride of Frankenstein").  Many here seem to think the Brendan Frasier films of the 90's were the originals but "The Mummy" was first made in 1932 and starred Boris Karloff.  Of course the Frasier film and this one have zero in common with the no explosions thriller of yore.  Doubt it would be seen by anyone except an indie theater audience if it were to be re-made shot for shot.  Check it out if in the mood for something  cerebral.  If not quite there, check out the 1940's mummy films with Lon Chaney Jr.  I recommend "The Mummy's Tomb" for beginners.

text: Looks like a pretty decent film, one I'm probably going to see.  Just don't call it "The Mummy". Co-opting that name is nothing more than a transparent attempt to attract a built in audience.  At least the 1999  Brendan Fraser vehicle bore a resemblance to the 1932 Boris Karloff classic.  From this trailer, the only thing linking this film to those is the fact that the antagonist is a thousand year old Middle Eastern with enormous powers who was once wrapped in linen.  The fact that she is female, NOT named Imhotep and most of her revenge occurs in a large, modern city and not in Egypt makes calling this movie "The Mummy" an insult to an American horror classic and one of the seminal works in film history.   Shame on the producers and Universal Pictures.

text: Watched this movie on nearby multiplex theatre on 3D. A one time watch good movie like Ovilion, Edge of Tomorrow; but definitely not a Last Samurai. Anyway the name "The Mummy" doesn't justify this movie. you can't put some Egyptian locations and hundreds of mummy (more of zombies) in a movie and called it the "The Mummy". üëπ The original 1999 movie was far better. It was fast, funny, focused and more team oriented. Brandon Fraser has a proper love interest, a side kick and a true fearless friend to battle the Mummy. But here Tom Cruise was fighting alone. Also very disappointed to see that London location was not justified, I mean where is Buckingham palace and Big Bang? overall 1 star for the visual effects, 1 star for Sofia Boutella and 1 star for Tom Cruise (really enjoy the nude scene; can't remember when last time I seen him full monty, Remidn me the torture scene from Casino Royale.). Total 3 star out of 5. And wait why Russel Crowe was in the movie? Don't find any logic.

text: I just saw this movie and to set any records straight this movie is nothing compared to the first Mummy with Imohtep and those creepy af mummies, it had good dialogue, good romantic dynamic, etc. But one thing I must say about this movie... it was genious, I was expecting a crappy reboot but I ended being astonished with what I just saw.     ((Spoilers))-->      1- Dr. Jekyll/Hyde - I did not expect that 2- I like the fact that there was a little comedy, not too much, (which was perfect) regarding Vail and him being cursed and all. Jake Johnson fits like a glove in that character. 3- I liked the jumpscares, the fact that this movie contains comedy and horror is just amazing I felt really good watching this movie. 4- That easter egg when Jenny was fighting the dude in the library and she smacked his face with the Book of Amun-Ra, that was brilliant. 5- Princess Ahmanet transforming the glass from the windows into a massive sandstorm was every bit brilliant, once glass is made from sand. And here this hoe did the complete opposite. 6- I liked the plot twist at the end. I'm honestly so tired of all those happy ending clich√©s, I end up standing on the bad guy's side every movie.  There are more aspects but i'm too lazy to describe..  Tom Cruise did a good job, he's always been a good actor. But I feel that they should've used a younger actor. (ofc Tom is old and experienced and perhaps the Director thought it would be good to have such experience on the movie, it worked out) I feel that Stephen Amell would fit like a glove here.

Then a fifth and sixth Mummy movie the fifth one coming out on July 1 2005 still taking place in Egypt which obviously every single movie should especially if it's about mummies.  Then the sixth and final last Mummy movie with Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, John Hannah, and Oded Fehr taking place in Egypt coming out sometime in July of 2007.  Then three years later after six in total Mummy movies with Brendan Fraser I think it would be a good time to do a reboot with Tom Cruise.
